@baseUrl = http://localhost:8080

# Set these to match IDs created by scenario.http (or your own setup)
@storeId = 1
@product1Id = 1

# =============================================================================
# Circuit Breaker Verification Scenario
#
# Prerequisites
#   - All four backend services and docker-compose DBs are running.
#   - storeId / product1Id above must match your data (check scenario.http run).
#
# CB config (notification instance)
#   sliding-window-size:              10 calls
#   minimum-number-of-calls:           5
#   failure-rate-threshold:           50 %  (5/5 = 100 % → opens immediately)
#   slow-call-duration-threshold:      3 s
#   wait-duration-in-open-state:      30 s
#   permitted-calls-in-half-open:      3
#
# Run steps in order top-to-bottom within each phase.
#
#   PHASE 0  Sign in
#   PHASE 1  CB CLOSED  — notification-service UP, real responses
#   PHASE 2  Trip the CB — stop notification-service, run [2-1]…[2-5] in sequence
#   PHASE 3  CB OPEN    — instant fallbacks, no network calls
#   PHASE 4  Recovery   — restart notification-service, circuit closes
# =============================================================================


# =============================================================================
# PHASE 0 — Sign in
# =============================================================================

### [0-1] Sign in — CUSTOMER  →  saves customerToken
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/users/signin
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "email": "mentee@example.com",
  "password": "password123"
}

> {%
client.global.set("customerToken", "Bearer " + response.body.accessToken);
%}

###

### [0-2] Sign in — OWNER  →  saves ownerToken
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/users/signin
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "email": "mentor@example.com",
  "password": "password123"
}

> {%
client.global.set("ownerToken", "Bearer " + response.body.accessToken);
%}

###


# =============================================================================
# PHASE 1 — CB CLOSED  (notification-service must be UP)
#
# Expected: all calls reach notification-service; real 200 responses.
# =============================================================================

### [1-1] List notifications — real response (200, [] if no data yet)
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/notifications/list
Authorization: {{customerToken}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "unreadOnly": false
}

###

### [1-2] Mark all read — real response (200)
PUT {{baseUrl}}/api/notifications/read-all
Authorization: {{customerToken}}

###

### [1-3] Add product to cart  →  saves cbCartId1
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/carts
Authorization: {{customerToken}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "productId": {{product1Id}},
  "storeId": {{storeId}},
  "quantity": 1
}

> {%
client.global.set("cbCartId1", response.body.id);
%}

###

### [1-4] Checkout — 200; createNotification fires async and succeeds
# CB state: CLOSED — notification is actually sent to notification-service
# Verify: notification-service logs show  POST /internal/notifications 201
PUT {{baseUrl}}/api/carts/checkout
Authorization: {{customerToken}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "cartId": {{cbCartId1}}
}

###


# =============================================================================
# PHASE 2 — Trip the circuit
#
# ACTION: Stop notification-service now (Ctrl+C in its terminal).
#
# Run [2-1] through [2-5] one by one.
# Each call blocks ~3 s (read timeout) then returns 200 [] via fallback.
# After [2-5]: 5 failures, 100 % rate ≥ 50 % threshold → circuit OPEN.
#
# Watch BFF logs for:
#   [CB] listMyNotifications fallback: ...
# =============================================================================

### [2-1] List — failure 1 of 5  (~3 s wait)
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/notifications/list
Authorization: {{customerToken}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "unreadOnly": false
}

###

### [2-2] List — failure 2 of 5  (~3 s wait)
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/notifications/list
Authorization: {{customerToken}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "unreadOnly": false
}

###

### [2-3] List — failure 3 of 5  (~3 s wait)
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/notifications/list
Authorization: {{customerToken}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "unreadOnly": false
}

###

### [2-4] List — failure 4 of 5  (~3 s wait)
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/notifications/list
Authorization: {{customerToken}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "unreadOnly": false
}

###

### [2-5] List — failure 5 of 5  (~3 s wait)  →  circuit OPEN after this
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/notifications/list
Authorization: {{customerToken}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "unreadOnly": false
}

###


# =============================================================================
# PHASE 3 — CB OPEN  (notification-service still DOWN)
#
# All notification calls return instantly — no network attempt.
# Order mutations (checkout) also return instantly.
# BFF logs show [CB] fallback messages.
# =============================================================================

### [3-1] List — instant 200 []  (fallback)
# BFF log: [CB] listMyNotifications fallback: CircuitBreaker 'notification' is OPEN ...
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/notifications/list
Authorization: {{customerToken}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "unreadOnly": false
}

###

### [3-2] Mark all read — instant 200  (fallback)
PUT {{baseUrl}}/api/notifications/read-all
Authorization: {{customerToken}}

###

### [3-3] Add product to cart  →  saves cbCartId2
# cbCartId1 is already ordered → this creates a fresh cart
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/carts
Authorization: {{customerToken}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "productId": {{product1Id}},
  "storeId": {{storeId}},
  "quantity": 1
}

> {%
client.global.set("cbCartId2", response.body.id);
%}

###

### [3-4] Checkout — instant 200, no 3 s wait for notification
# CB state: OPEN — createNotification fast-fails via CallNotPermittedException
# Order is created normally; async notification is skipped
# BFF log: [CB] createNotification skipped (CallNotPermittedException): ...
PUT {{baseUrl}}/api/carts/checkout
Authorization: {{customerToken}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "cartId": {{cbCartId2}}
}

###


# =============================================================================
# PHASE 4 — Recovery
#
# ACTION: Wait 30 s (automatic OPEN → HALF_OPEN transition).
# ACTION: Restart notification-service.
#
# The next 3 list calls are probes. All succeed → circuit CLOSED.
# =============================================================================

### [4-1] List — probe 1 of 3  (HALF_OPEN)
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/notifications/list
Authorization: {{customerToken}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "unreadOnly": false
}

###

### [4-2] List — probe 2 of 3
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/notifications/list
Authorization: {{customerToken}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "unreadOnly": false
}

###

### [4-3] List — probe 3 of 3  →  circuit CLOSED after this
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/notifications/list
Authorization: {{customerToken}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "unreadOnly": false
}

###

### [4-4] Add product to cart  →  saves cbCartId3
# cbCartId2 is already ordered → this creates a fresh cart
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/carts
Authorization: {{customerToken}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "productId": {{product1Id}},
  "storeId": {{storeId}},
  "quantity": 1
}

> {%
client.global.set("cbCartId3", response.body.id);
%}

###

### [4-5] Checkout — 200; notification delivered (circuit CLOSED)
# BFF log: no [CB] fallback → real notification sent
# notification-service log: POST /internal/notifications 201
PUT {{baseUrl}}/api/carts/checkout
Authorization: {{customerToken}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "cartId": {{cbCartId3}}
}

###
